{{Infobox journal | cover = | discipline = [[History]] | editor = | language = | abbreviation =Afr. Sources Afr. Hist. | publisher = Brill | country = | history = Since 2001 | website = http://www.brill.com/publications/african-sources-african-history | ISSN = 1567-6951 }} '''''African Sources for African History''''' is a [[Monographic series|book series]] published by [[Brill Publishers|Brill]] that aims to make available [[critical edition]]s of indigenous African narrative sources from [[sub-Saharan Africa]].<ref>[http://www.brill.com/publications/african-sources-african-history African Sources for African History] Brill, 2014. Retrieved 17 May 2014.</ref> The series aims to expand the sources available to historians of Africa, and to rectify bias that may have been introduced into the writing of [[African history]] through an over-reliance on sources written by Europeans.
The first in the series was the 2001 ''Somono Bala of the Upper Niger'', an epic story of fishing people, translated into English from the [[Maninka]] language for the first time.
