The '''Blaauboschkraal stone ruins''', also known as '''Adam's Calendar'''<ref name=news24>https://www.news24.com/SciTech/Human-genesis-is-alien-SA-author-20110309</ref><ref name=hp>https://www.huffingtonpost.com/gaiam-tv/lost-civilization_b_2095209.html</ref><ref name=abs>http://atlantablackstar.com/2014/06/27/6-ancient-african-architectural-marvels-built-before-greece-or-rome-existed/</ref> are a [[provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]] in [[Waterval Boven]] in the [[Mpumalanga]] province of [[South Africa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sahra.org.za/sahris/sites/922820008 |title=9/2/282/0008 Stone ruins, Blaauboschkraal, Waterval Boven District |author= |format= |pages= |date= |accessdate=2018-05-22 |quote= |publisher=South African Heritage Resources Agency }}</ref> The site was originally declared a national monument on 18 April 1975.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sahra.org.za/sahris/node/33748 |title=Stone ruins, Blaauboschkraal, Waterval Boven District |author= |format= |pages= |date= |accessdate=2018-05-22 |quote= |publisher=South African Heritage Resources Agency }}</ref><ref name="Gazette">{{cite journal |url=http://www.sahra.org.za/sahris/sites/default/files/gazettes/4667-725%20Stone%20Ruins%2C%20Blaauboschkraal%2C%20Waterval%20Boven.pdf |author= J. P. van der Spuy |title=No. 725 Declaration of a National Monument | journal =Government Gazette of South Africa | volume = | issue =4667 | pages =18 |date =18 April 1975 |doi = |accessdate=2018-05-25 |quote= |work= }}</ref>

The ruins are the remains of structures created by people who settled the region in the 16th century and who altered the landscape to increase agricultural yields in high-altitude grasslands.<ref name="bokoni">{{cite news |author=Amanda Esterhuysen |title=The Bokoni story unearthed |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2015-02-26-the-bokoni-story-unearthed |quote= |pages= |work=Mail and Guardian |location= |date=27 February 2015 |accessdate=2018-05-22 }}</ref> The stone rings are believed to have been used as enclosures for cattle ([[kraal]]s).<ref name="Gazette"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/article/prehistory-nelspruit-area |title=Prehistory of the Nelspruit area |author=T. N. Huffman |format= |pages= |date=11 August 2017 |accessdate=2018-05-25 |quote= |publisher=South African History Online }}</ref>

The Blaauboskraal stone ruins are among a number of stone circle ruins located in the Mpumalanga [[Great Escarpment, Southern Africa|escarpment]] over an area of approximately 150 km<sup>2</sup>, a number of which are facing threats to conservation.<ref>{{cite news |author=Sizwe sama Yende |title=Heritage under threat |url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/heritage-under-threat-20170916 |quote= |pages= |work=News 24/City Press |location= |date=2017-09-17 |accessdate=2018-05-25 }}</ref>

Information about the people who created these stone circles and terraces was often omitted from South African historical sources.<ref name="bokoni"/>

==Alternate theories==
Alternate theories exist of alien or ancient origins.  The most prominent proponent of an alternate origin, politician [[Michael Tellinger]], calls the site "Adam's Calendar" and claims they are remains of the oldest man-made site in the world built by [[Enki]] 300,000 years ago as an ancient calendar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atlasobscura.com/places/adams-calendar|title=Adam's Calendar|website=Atlas Obscura}}</ref><ref name=news24/><ref name=hp/><ref name=abs/>

